./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2098:   344	- 2026-04-26 [codex-prompts][contract] **Reusable contract snippets + a one-command assembly helper end the per-prompt boilerplate-drift failure mode.** Sprint 7h-3 landed `~/.cursor-daybook-sync/codex-prompts/` with 6 versioned contract snippets (SCOPE_FENCE, BRANCH_HYGIENE, GREEN_CHECKS, FINAL_LINE, VENV, LIVE_TENANT), 3 composite headers (OFFLINE / OFFLINE_READONLY / LIVE), and `codex_prompt.sh` that substitutes `${WORKSPACE}` / `${BRANCH}` / `${BASE}` and launches the right driver. Pattern: every prompt becomes a body-only file (goal + files + steps + commit message) that gets pre-pended with one of the headers. Saves ~1k tokens per prompt write + ~1k per worker re-read of duplicated rules. Drift policy: snippet edits bump the version-date and require a LESSONS entry tagged `[codex-prompts][contract]`; per-task bodies never duplicate contract content. The library is itself the discipline surface — workers that bypass the helper are the failure mode worth catching.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2121:   367	- 2026-04-26 [codex-prompts][preamble] **Single `AGENT_PREAMBLE.md` cat'd before the header is the missing layer below per-task templates.** Per the daybook skill's `references/orchestration.md` recommendation, build one preamble file every worker reads first. Lists step-zero ritual (read JOURNAL head + LESSONS tail + git status), DONE-dump format, 3-attempt stop rule, daybook ownership, scope-fence, secret redaction. Saves ~700 tokens per prompt (no longer inlined per-task). Updates propagate to next worker for free. `codex_prompt.sh` gains `--with-preamble` flag for opt-in.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2124:   370	- 2026-04-26 [coverage] Sealed skeletons inside `--cov=keeper_sdk` need contract tests in the landing slice, not a later ratchet cleanup. (LESSON CANDIDATE from bus.py memo worker — captured here, parent applies on the bus.py Option B slice.)
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2127:   373	- 2026-04-26 [daybook][clobber-regression][closed] **Post-push state file (`.sync-state.json`) + working-tree blob walk catches silent JOURNAL/LESSONS reversion.** Mechanism: `sync_daybook.sh` writes `head_sha` + `journal_blob` + `lessons_blob` per push; `daybook_clobber_verify.sh` compares current `git hash-object <file>` to recorded blob; if they differ AND the current blob exists as a HISTORICAL blob in the file's git-log, working tree has regressed (clobbered by external writer between syncs). Wired into `agent_pre_claim.sh` so every claim re-checks. Triggered twice in 7h-9 → 7h-10 sequence: sync pushed +44 lines, working-tree later reverted to 866 lines (lost 42); recovered via `git checkout HEAD -- JOURNAL.md` both times. Likely root cause: stale Cursor/editor buffer auto-saved over the symlink target. The verify is structural; the prevention (force fresh-read before any external write) is not enforceable from the daybook side.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2136:   382	- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][safe-launch-wrapper] **A pre-flight wrapper that refuses on dirty-tree + unpushed-commits closes the worker step-zero race deterministically; rule reminders alone do not.** Sprint 7h-12 LESSONS [worker][step-zero-race] documented the failure mode (first P9 worker launch failed READONLY-FAIL because parent's commit hadn't landed yet). Sprint 7h-13 fix: `codex_safe_launch.sh` reads `git status --porcelain` (must be empty) AND `git rev-list --count @{u}..HEAD` (must be 0); refuses with explicit override flags `--allow-dirty` / `--allow-unpushed`. Wrapper exec's the underlying launcher only when checks pass. Calling pattern stays one command, just one indirection deeper. Pattern: any "do X only when state Y holds" rule that fires across sessions should live in a wrapper script not a rule reminder — wrappers compose into pipelines, reminders rely on agent recall. Add as a habit: when documenting a recurring pre-condition violation in LESSONS, audit whether a wrapper script could turn it into a hard refusal.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2143:   389	- 2026-04-26 [schema][uid-ref-uniqueness-semantic] **JSON Schema cannot enforce `uid_ref` uniqueness across sibling arrays (e.g. `records[].uid_ref` cannot collide with `record_types[].uid_ref` in the same manifest); the family's test module must carry a semantic-collision check until typed-model parsing owns the invariant.** Sprint 7h-14 P9 vault.v1 worker DONE-dump LESSON CANDIDATE: `keeper-vault.v1` has 4 top-level keys (`records`, `record_types`, `attachments`, `keeper_fill`) each with `uid_ref` fields and the planner expects globally-unique uid_refs across the whole manifest. JSON Schema's `uniqueItems` is per-array; cross-array uniqueness is undecidable in pure Schema. Worker added an explicit pytest case (`test_keeper_vault_schema_rejects_uid_ref_collisions`) that walks all four arrays and asserts `len(uid_refs) == len(set(uid_refs))`, raising `SchemaError` with field name in the reason. Pattern: any schema family with cross-block identifier uniqueness needs (a) a documented gap-comment in the schema JSON saying which invariant is enforced semantically not structurally, and (b) a test module that asserts the invariant at the family level. Future P10/P11/P13 schemas with `uid_ref` should follow the same dual pattern.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2146:   392	- 2026-04-26 [worker][format-on-rebase-jsonc-trap] **`ruff format` over a directory containing JSON schemas can introduce JSONC trailing commas into otherwise-valid JSON.** P10 worker's LESSON CANDIDATE flagged this: the worker's pre-commit autoformat hook ran `ruff format keeper_sdk` and the schema body file (under that path) gained trailing commas inside `enum` arrays. The 17 tests still passed because pytest's loader is tolerant, but `json.tool` would fail. Pattern: scope `ruff format` to `--include='*.py'` explicitly, OR exclude `*/schemas/*.json` paths in `pyproject.toml [tool.ruff] extend-exclude`. Add a `python -m json.tool < <path>` guard to CI for schemas. Worker correctly self-flagged; parent must add the exclude rule before it bites a future slice that depends on strict JSON parsing (e.g. external schema validators).
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2150:   396	- 2026-04-26 [process][optimization-batch-cadence] **A dedicated process-optimization sprint, scheduled deliberately and bounded to cheap+compounding picks, returns ROI by the 2nd downstream slice.** Sprint 7h-16 paused product velocity for one cycle to land 3 picks: (A) `keeper_sdk/core/schemas/CONVENTIONS.md` removes ~30% of redundant context per per-family worker task body, (B) `python -m json.tool` schema-validate CI job catches the JSONC trailing-comma trap from Sprint 7h-15 LESSON `[worker][format-on-rebase-jsonc-trap]` BEFORE merge instead of locally, (C) `dsk_ship.sh` end-to-end ship wrapper replaces a 4-step manual sequence with idempotent exit-coded automation. ROI math: A amortizes at slice 2 (5+ schema slices remain), B amortizes at slice 1 (caught zero violations this run but is now structural), C amortizes at ship 2 (already revealed 2 latent bugs in its debut). The pattern: budget 1 cycle of every ~5-8 product cycles for explicit process review; reject anything that looks like enforcement rather than acceleration (skipped: memo→amendment auto-check, weekly auto-prune — both add gates without removing work).
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2153:   399	- 2026-04-26 [conventions-doc][reduces-task-body-overhead] **A single canonical CONVENTIONS doc inside the artifact directory it governs (here: `keeper_sdk/core/schemas/CONVENTIONS.md`) removes ~30% of per-task redundant context.** Before: every P*-impl task body re-derived `additionalProperties: false`, `x-keeper-live-proof` block shape, `$id` pattern, cross-family ref grammar, `uid_ref` semantic uniqueness pattern, `$comment` TODO marker convention, commit-message format. After: task body cites CONVENTIONS by path; worker reads it first; task body shrinks to the family-specific scope only. Workers propose amendments via DONE-dump LESSON CANDIDATE; parent integrates after 2+ families hit the same pattern (don't amend on a single-family quirk). Pattern: when 3+ artifact instances share 80%+ of their construction rules, factor the rules into a CONVENTIONS doc colocated with the artifacts. The doc becomes parent-owned; workers cite, don't edit.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2154:   400	- 2026-04-26 [ci-guard][stdlib-strict-vs-tolerant-parsers] **The `python -m json.tool` CI guard catches the JSONC trailing-comma class of bugs that `pytest`'s lenient parser tolerates.** Sprint 7h-15 LESSON `[worker][format-on-rebase-jsonc-trap]` warned `ruff format` over the schemas dir introduces JSONC trailing commas. Pytest's `json.load` (via `keeper_sdk.core.schemas`) silently tolerates them; external strict parsers (RFC 8259) reject. Adding the strict guard to `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (`schema-validate` job, `build` depends on it) shifts the discovery from "downstream consumer breakage" to "CI fail on the PR before merge". General pattern: every artifact format read by both lenient + strict parsers needs a CI-time strict-parser guard. Don't rely on the test suite for format-validity if the test suite uses the lenient parser. Other candidates in this codebase: `dsk validate <yaml>` already uses strict YAML; `examples/*.yaml` are guarded; what about `pyproject.toml` (toml)? `docs/*.md` (markdown frontmatter)? Audit when next bites.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2168:   414	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-codex-fanout] **4 codex offline-bg + 1 Task subagent in parallel produced 4 cross-cited memos in ~5 min wall-clock and surfaced 1 immediately-landable schema drift fix (`bffa01b`).** Sprint 7h-36 fired: CDX-1 (multi-profile refactor), CDX-2 (concurrency audit), CDX-3 (capability census), CDX-4 (vault scenario design), Task agent (repo review summary). Wall-clock dominated by single-worker latency, so N parallel ≈ 1× sequential time. Total tokens used per worker logged in marker (CDX-2: 105k, CDX-3: 173k). Pattern: when investigation prompts are independent, well-scoped, cite-required (`file:line` mandatory in deliverable shape), and READONLY, parallel readonly fan-out is high-ROI vs serial codex_offline + serial parent reads. Anti-pattern: parallel WRITE-mode codex against same repo without git-worktree-per-worker (LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]` from 7h-3.1 already documented the sandbox-gitdir issue). Cap at ~5 parallel readonly to keep parent context under 200k when harvesting.
