./docs/sprint-memos/7h-42-V7d-split-review.codex.log:3989:  6247	   437	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][daybook-debt-via-readonly-codex] **Pending daybook-infra debt is perfect for parallel-readonly codex slices that run alongside write-mode slices for free.** The 7h-39 V4 regex-tightening memo took ~2min wall for a cite-rich, patch-ready, test-included memo. Parent applied directly. Pattern: every sprint with N write workers should also fire 1-2 readonly slices targeting daybook-debt or design memos. They don't conflict with anything; ROI > zero. Closes the orchestration gap that pending items sat for sprints because no codex slot was scheduled for them.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-42-V7d-split-review.codex.log:3991:  6249	   439	- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-tightening] **Count pending daybook debt from the canonical Pending decisions section in WORKTREES.md with section-state parsing, not append-only JOURNAL/LESSONS substring scans that preserve historical references forever.** Section-parser enters on `^##\s+Pending decisions\b`, exits on next `^##\s+`, counts unchecked checkbox + numbered rows that are NOT closed (`~~`, `**DONE`, `[x]`, `_[CLOSED`). 5-case offline test at `~/.cursor-daybook-sync/scripts/test_pending_count.py`. Closes 7h-35 LESSON `[daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation]`. Migration risk audited at `agent_review_loop.py` callers + boot/stop hooks; review-latest is fail-open so a broken patch couldn't block session close anyway.
