./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6210:   400	- 2026-04-26 [ci-guard][stdlib-strict-vs-tolerant-parsers] **The `python -m json.tool` CI guard catches the JSONC trailing-comma class of bugs that `pytest`'s lenient parser tolerates.** Sprint 7h-15 LESSON `[worker][format-on-rebase-jsonc-trap]` warned `ruff format` over the schemas dir introduces JSONC trailing commas. Pytest's `json.load` (via `keeper_sdk.core.schemas`) silently tolerates them; external strict parsers (RFC 8259) reject. Adding the strict guard to `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (`schema-validate` job, `build` depends on it) shifts the discovery from "downstream consumer breakage" to "CI fail on the PR before merge". General pattern: every artifact format read by both lenient + strict parsers needs a CI-time strict-parser guard. Don't rely on the test suite for format-validity if the test suite uses the lenient parser. Other candidates in this codebase: `dsk validate <yaml>` already uses strict YAML; `examples/*.yaml` are guarded; what about `pyproject.toml` (toml)? `docs/*.md` (markdown frontmatter)? Audit when next bites.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6224:   414	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-codex-fanout] **4 codex offline-bg + 1 Task subagent in parallel produced 4 cross-cited memos in ~5 min wall-clock and surfaced 1 immediately-landable schema drift fix (`bffa01b`).** Sprint 7h-36 fired: CDX-1 (multi-profile refactor), CDX-2 (concurrency audit), CDX-3 (capability census), CDX-4 (vault scenario design), Task agent (repo review summary). Wall-clock dominated by single-worker latency, so N parallel ≈ 1× sequential time. Total tokens used per worker logged in marker (CDX-2: 105k, CDX-3: 173k). Pattern: when investigation prompts are independent, well-scoped, cite-required (`file:line` mandatory in deliverable shape), and READONLY, parallel readonly fan-out is high-ROI vs serial codex_offline + serial parent reads. Anti-pattern: parallel WRITE-mode codex against same repo without git-worktree-per-worker (LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]` from 7h-3.1 already documented the sandbox-gitdir issue). Cap at ~5 parallel readonly to keep parent context under 200k when harvesting.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6230:   420	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-write-fanout] **4-way parallel codex (2 write-mode worktrees + 2 readonly memos) is the right unit for one sprint when slices share a file surface; parent owns the conflict weave.** Sprint 7h-37 ran S1 (`cursor/smoke-multiprofile`) + S2 (`cursor/vault-smoke-vaultOneLogin`) write workers concurrently, both touching `scripts/smoke/smoke.py` and `keeper_sdk/core/diff.py`. The 5 conflict regions resolved cleanly under one rule: "PAM path = profile-aware (S1); vault path = S2 plumbed onto S1's `run_context.title_prefix`". Wall time: ~15min total (longest worker = S1 ~13min). Orchestrator time: ~25min (worker launch + poll + merge weave + push + cleanup). Throughput ROI vs serial: at least 2x because S2 + memos run while S1 churns through ruff/pytest/mypy. Pattern: worktree-per-slice + cite-rich prompt + worker self-pushes its branch + parent owns merge-with-rule. Anti-pattern: trying to merge a worker branch via `gh pr` when `gh` isn't installed — direct `git merge --no-ff` of `origin/<branch>` works and is faster.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6232:   422	- 2026-04-27 [smoke][family-dispatch-vs-profile-orthogonality] **`VaultScenarioSpec` + `_ACTIVE_SCENARIO_FAMILY` are orthogonal axes to `SmokeProfile`; merge weave rule is "vault path consumes `run_context.title_prefix`, not module-level `TITLE_PREFIX`".** When two slices add new dimensions to the same module (S1 = profile dimension, S2 = scenario-family dimension), both dimensions must compose. The `_active_resources()` function gains both a profile-context arg AND a family guard; `_write_manifest()` branches on family AND threads profile; cleanup branches on family AND uses `run_context.project_name`. Anti-pattern: keeping the S2 vault path on `TITLE_PREFIX` after S1 plumbed `run_context.title_prefix` — it would silently regress profile isolation for vault scenarios on a future profile run. Cite: `scripts/smoke/smoke.py` after `11a48ae`, the "vault folder selected" branch and `_active_vault_scenario().verify(typed, live, run_context.title_prefix)` call.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6239:   429	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][live-worker-may-bypass-linked-worktree-ref] **A codex live-mode worker can land its commit on `origin/<branch>` without updating the linked-worktree's local branch ref or clearing its working-tree diff.** Symptoms after worker reports DONE: `git ls-remote origin <branch>` shows new SHA, but in the linked worktree `git log` shows the OLD base SHA and `git status` shows the same files as " M" (modified vs HEAD). Cause: live-mode codex appears to commit via plumbing or its own gitdir handling (different from offline-bg's auto-add-dir patch from LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]`). Recovery: skip the worktree entirely — parent merges `origin/<branch>` directly from the primary repo with `git merge --no-ff origin/<branch>`, then runs pytest in primary, pushes, and `git worktree remove --force` the dirty linked tree. The dirty diff there is just a stale copy of what's now on main, so `--force` removal is safe. Don't try to reconcile the linked worktree's HEAD — it's a distraction. Future fix in `codex_live.sh`: print local HEAD + remote HEAD after commit so the parent can spot the divergence in the launcher log immediately.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6243:   433	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][archive-codex-artifacts] **Every sprint's codex prompts (`/tmp/dsk-*.md`) and worker logs (`/tmp/codex-*.log`) are ephemeral; archive eagerly to `docs/sprint-memos/`.** A single reboot otherwise loses cite-rich prompt patterns that took ~120 LOC each to write. Parent step ~3min/sprint: copy `*.prompt.md` files plus `tail -200..400` of write-worker logs (full logs of readonly memo workers stay reasonable). Established 7h-39 with retroactive backfill of 7h-37 + 7h-38. Future agents reuse the prompt patterns as templates and read the post-mortem tails to learn how previous workers self-fixed bugs during live runs.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6245:   435	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-write-3way-conflict-pattern] **Three write workers extending the same public function signature + same enum produce 8-12 conflict regions per merge — plan for it.** Sprint 7h-39 V1+V2+V3 all extended `compute_vault_diff` kwargs and all re-added duplicate `ChangeKind.SKIP` directives. Mitigations: (a) tell each worker that signature kwarg additions are PARENT's merge job, not theirs (helps); (b) consolidate enum additions into a separate parent-only commit BEFORE fan-out (best); (c) when conflicts arrive, rewrite the file as a full-file `Write` with helpers in canonical order rather than line-by-line conflict-marker editing (faster and produces a clean diff for review). 3-way merge wall ~5min with these.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6247:   437	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][daybook-debt-via-readonly-codex] **Pending daybook-infra debt is perfect for parallel-readonly codex slices that run alongside write-mode slices for free.** The 7h-39 V4 regex-tightening memo took ~2min wall for a cite-rich, patch-ready, test-included memo. Parent applied directly. Pattern: every sprint with N write workers should also fire 1-2 readonly slices targeting daybook-debt or design memos. They don't conflict with anything; ROI > zero. Closes the orchestration gap that pending items sat for sprints because no codex slot was scheduled for them.
