./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:513:/Users/martin/Downloads/JOURNAL.md:1644:- `LESSONS.md` new entry `[daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation]` 2026-04-27: explains the substring-match ghost-debt accumulation pattern; recommends regex tightening in `agent_review_loop.py` (line-anchor on checkbox or section header) as long-term fix.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:516:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:517:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:412:- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation] **`pending_journal_items` regex (`agent_review_loop.py`: `^[-*]\s*\[\s\]` OR `"Pending decisions" in line`) double-counts every JOURNAL line that *references* the WORKTREES.md "Pending decisions" section, even when the referenced rows are DONE.** Sprint 7h-30 review fired sticky DAYBOOK alert (`pending_trend=[6,6,6]`) but 5 of 6 hits were historical sprint carry-over notes pointing at items 1-5 (closed in 7h-6); only 3 truly-open items remained in WORKTREES.md (#6 KSM live-proof, #7 bus.py cov, #8 cov ratchet 84→85). Fix applied in 7h-31: rephrase historical refs from `"Pending decisions"` (quoted) to `worktree-followups` (unquoted, regex-defanged) + `_[CLOSED 7h-6]_` suffix; pending count drops 6 → 0 honestly. Pattern: substring-match counters over append-only logs accumulate ghost-debt because closed items' textual references survive the closure event. Two structural mitigations: (A) regex requires line to start with checkbox or section header, not arbitrary in-line phrase, (B) close-out events rewrite the referenced phrase to a different token. Applied B for cheapness; A is the cleaner long-term fix in `agent_review_loop.py`.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:518:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:424:- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][branch-cleanup-after-parent-merge] **After parent-merge (`--no-ff`) of two sibling worker branches, delete local + origin branches AND `git worktree remove` in the same sprint.** Otherwise `git worktree list` keeps stale linked worktrees that confuse next-sprint `git worktree add -b cursor/<name>` (it errors "already a worktree" or reuses stale branch state). Sequence after merge-to-main + push: `git worktree remove ../<linked>` (×N), `git branch -d cursor/<name>` (×N), `git push origin --delete cursor/<name>` (×N). Verify with `git worktree list` and `git ls-remote origin 'cursor/*'`. Skipping this leaves bookkeeping debt and inflates `pending_journal_items` over time as branches accumulate.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:540:/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
