./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:875:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:412:- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation] **`pending_journal_items` regex (`agent_review_loop.py`: `^[-*]\s*\[\s\]` OR `"Pending decisions" in line`) double-counts every JOURNAL line that *references* the WORKTREES.md "Pending decisions" section, even when the referenced rows are DONE.** Sprint 7h-30 review fired sticky DAYBOOK alert (`pending_trend=[6,6,6]`) but 5 of 6 hits were historical sprint carry-over notes pointing at items 1-5 (closed in 7h-6); only 3 truly-open items remained in WORKTREES.md (#6 KSM live-proof, #7 bus.py cov, #8 cov ratchet 84→85). Fix applied in 7h-31: rephrase historical refs from `"Pending decisions"` (quoted) to `worktree-followups` (unquoted, regex-defanged) + `_[CLOSED 7h-6]_` suffix; pending count drops 6 → 0 honestly. Pattern: substring-match counters over append-only logs accumulate ghost-debt because closed items' textual references survive the closure event. Two structural mitigations: (A) regex requires line to start with checkbox or section header, not arbitrary in-line phrase, (B) close-out events rewrite the referenced phrase to a different token. Applied B for cheapness; A is the cleaner long-term fix in `agent_review_loop.py`.
