./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:1022:   414	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-codex-fanout] **4 codex offline-bg + 1 Task subagent in parallel produced 4 cross-cited memos in ~5 min wall-clock and surfaced 1 immediately-landable schema drift fix (`bffa01b`).** Sprint 7h-36 fired: CDX-1 (multi-profile refactor), CDX-2 (concurrency audit), CDX-3 (capability census), CDX-4 (vault scenario design), Task agent (repo review summary). Wall-clock dominated by single-worker latency, so N parallel ≈ 1× sequential time. Total tokens used per worker logged in marker (CDX-2: 105k, CDX-3: 173k). Pattern: when investigation prompts are independent, well-scoped, cite-required (`file:line` mandatory in deliverable shape), and READONLY, parallel readonly fan-out is high-ROI vs serial codex_offline + serial parent reads. Anti-pattern: parallel WRITE-mode codex against same repo without git-worktree-per-worker (LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]` from 7h-3.1 already documented the sandbox-gitdir issue). Cap at ~5 parallel readonly to keep parent context under 200k when harvesting.
./docs/sprint-memos/7h-39-V4-regex-memo.codex.log:1025:   420	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-write-fanout] **4-way parallel codex (2 write-mode worktrees + 2 readonly memos) is the right unit for one sprint when slices share a file surface; parent owns the conflict weave.** Sprint 7h-37 ran S1 (`cursor/smoke-multiprofile`) + S2 (`cursor/vault-smoke-vaultOneLogin`) write workers concurrently, both touching `scripts/smoke/smoke.py` and `keeper_sdk/core/diff.py`. The 5 conflict regions resolved cleanly under one rule: "PAM path = profile-aware (S1); vault path = S2 plumbed onto S1's `run_context.title_prefix`". Wall time: ~15min total (longest worker = S1 ~13min). Orchestrator time: ~25min (worker launch + poll + merge weave + push + cleanup). Throughput ROI vs serial: at least 2x because S2 + memos run while S1 churns through ruff/pytest/mypy. Pattern: worktree-per-slice + cite-rich prompt + worker self-pushes its branch + parent owns merge-with-rule. Anti-pattern: trying to merge a worker branch via `gh pr` when `gh` isn't installed — direct `git merge --no-ff` of `origin/<branch>` works and is faster.
