docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2101:   347	- 2026-04-26 [codex-sandbox][worktree-gitdir] **Codex `sandbox_mode = "workspace-write"` blocks linked-worktree commits because the gitdir lives in `<primary>/.git/worktrees/<n>/`, OUTSIDE the workspace root.** Fail signature: `Unable to create .../.git/worktrees/<name>/index.lock: Operation not permitted` at the `git commit` step, even though pytest / mypy / ruff all pass. Structural fix: auto-detect the gitdir via `git rev-parse --git-dir` and pass it as `--add-dir <path>` to `codex exec` (codex's `--add-dir` is the documented way to extend writable roots beyond the cwd). `~/.cursor-daybook-sync/scripts/codex_offline.sh` now mirrors the `codex_live.sh` pattern: a `EXTRA_DIRS=()` array with auto-detected gitdir + optional `CODEX_OFFLINE_EXTRA_DIRS` env extension. Without this, every worker on a linked worktree silently fails at commit despite green checks — wasted token spend on what looks like a ready-to-merge slice. Pattern: any sandbox tightening that defaults to "cwd-only" needs an explicit allow-list mechanism for tooling-required side paths (gitdir, `~/.config`, lockfiles); don't assume the cwd is sufficient.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2105:   351	- 2026-04-26 [codex-sandbox][shared-object-store] **Linked worktrees need TWO directories writable beyond the cwd, not one: the per-worktree gitdir (`<primary>/.git/worktrees/<n>/`) AND the common gitdir (`<primary>/.git/`).** First fix patched `codex_offline.sh` to add only the per-worktree gitdir from `git rev-parse --git-dir`; workers immediately hit a second `Operation not permitted` writing blobs to `<primary>/.git/objects/`. The common gitdir holds the shared object store + refs that every linked worktree commits into. Final fix: also auto-add `git rev-parse --git-common-dir` (with dedup when equal to per-worktree gitdir for normal clones). Pattern: when sandbox-tightening blocks ANY git operation in a linked worktree, the answer is always BOTH gitdirs (`--git-dir` + `--git-common-dir`); a partial fix that only adds one is a recurring failure mode that re-bites at the next operation. Verified by 3 cov slices (redact, schema, normalize) all landing successfully via parent-commit in the same session — workers only need to be re-launched if the deliverable itself is wrong, not if the tooling layer is busted.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2111:   357	- 2026-04-26 [branch-stack][pollution] **A branch created with HEAD on a non-main branch will silently inherit that ancestor's commits, polluting the PR diff and breaking CI on repo-wide checks (ruff format, mypy) even when the slice diff is clean.** Sprint 7h-5: 3 cov branches (`cov-redact-patterns`, `cov-schema-validation`, `cov-normalize-edges`) were created while parent was on `cursor/sdk-ksm-bootstrap`, dragging in 3 KSM commits and 3 unformatted KSM files (`auth/helper.py`, `secrets/ksm.py`, `_fakes/commander.py`). PRs targeted `main`, but `ruff format --check .` runs repo-wide, so the inherited unformatted files tripped the lint check despite the slice diff being immaculate. Diagnostic: `git log --oneline origin/main..origin/cursor/<branch>` shows the polluted ancestry — should be exactly 1 commit for a single-slice branch. Fix: `git rebase --onto origin/main <pollution-tip-sha> cursor/<branch>` drops the polluting commits and leaves only the slice on top of main. Pattern: every worker-spawn helper (`codex_offline.sh`, `git worktree add`) should explicitly `git checkout main && git pull` BEFORE creating the new branch, or pass `git worktree add -b <new> <path> origin/main` to pin the base. Scope-fence + branch-hygiene contracts already say "branch from main" in prose; needs to be enforced structurally in the helper scripts. Verifiable post-rebase: file count delta vs main matches the slice's expected file count (e.g. `git diff --name-only main...HEAD` lists only the slice's files). Future: add a slice-precommit check that fails if `git merge-base <branch> origin/main != origin/main`'s recent HEAD (i.e. the branch is N commits ahead of a stale main rather than the current main).
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2122:   368	- 2026-04-26 [codex-cli][bg-detach] **Background launchers must use `nohup` + runner-script + redirect-from-/dev/null, not `( ... ) &`.** Cursor's Shell tool starts a fresh bash per command that exits when the command returns. Naive `( ... ) &` subshells inherit that bash as their parent and catch SIGHUP when it exits — the cleanup block (writing `STATE=DONE` to the marker) never runs. First version of `codex_offline_bg.sh` had this bug; bus.py worker completed a clean READONLY-OK memo in the log but the marker stayed `LAUNCHED` forever. Fix: write the codex command + cleanup into a runner script (`/tmp/codex-offline-<ts>-<pid>.runner.sh`) and launch via `nohup bash $RUNNER </dev/null >/dev/null 2>&1 &`. `disown` alone is not enough on macOS bash inside an exiting parent. Verified: trivial test prompt now writes `STATE=DONE EXIT_CODE=0` correctly within seconds of codex finishing.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2133:   379	- 2026-04-26 [live-test][skip-by-default] **Live-tenant tests collected only when `KEEPER_LIVE_TENANT=1` AND each test's declared `requires=(...)` env vars are present; gate enforced at pytest-collection time, not runtime.** `tests/live/conftest.py` walks every collected item, looks for `pytest.mark.live(requires=(...))`, and adds a skip marker if `KEEPER_LIVE_TENANT` isn't `1` or any required env var is missing. Why collection-time vs runtime: a runtime check (`if not os.environ.get(...): pytest.skip(...)`) still imports the test module, runs fixtures, and shows the test in the report as "skipped" with a Python-level reason — workable but noisier and import-time crashes leak. Collection-time skip means `pytest tests/` reports exactly one skipped item per live test, no fixture work, no module-level imports of live-only deps. Pattern: any test category that depends on out-of-band setup (creds, GPU, network) should gate at collection so the default offline run is metrics-clean.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2139:   385	- 2026-04-26 [orchestration][parallel-readonly-memos] **4 parallel offline-readonly Codex workers complete in wall-time bounded by the largest single worker, not summed; on a clean main with shared workspace, no per-worker worktree is needed.** Sprint 7h-14: 4 schema-design memos (P10/P11/P12/P13 of V2 lineup) dispatched simultaneously via `codex_safe_launch.sh --repo "$SDK"` against a single clean `main` checkout. P11 (largest scope, enterprise) finished at 4min; P12/P13/P10 finished within 1min of P11. Total wall: ~5min vs ~30+ min serial. Shared workspace works because read-only workers can't collide on writes; the parent just extracts each worker's stdout from `/tmp/codex-offline-*-<pid>.log`. Pattern: (a) read-only workers parallelize trivially, share workspace; (b) write workers need worktrees + serial execution per branch; (c) wall-time predictor for parallel readonly = max(per-worker estimate), not sum. Practical implication: when the parent is between product slices and has 3+ research questions queued, ALWAYS dispatch them in parallel rather than asking sequentially.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2168:   414	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-codex-fanout] **4 codex offline-bg + 1 Task subagent in parallel produced 4 cross-cited memos in ~5 min wall-clock and surfaced 1 immediately-landable schema drift fix (`bffa01b`).** Sprint 7h-36 fired: CDX-1 (multi-profile refactor), CDX-2 (concurrency audit), CDX-3 (capability census), CDX-4 (vault scenario design), Task agent (repo review summary). Wall-clock dominated by single-worker latency, so N parallel ≈ 1× sequential time. Total tokens used per worker logged in marker (CDX-2: 105k, CDX-3: 173k). Pattern: when investigation prompts are independent, well-scoped, cite-required (`file:line` mandatory in deliverable shape), and READONLY, parallel readonly fan-out is high-ROI vs serial codex_offline + serial parent reads. Anti-pattern: parallel WRITE-mode codex against same repo without git-worktree-per-worker (LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]` from 7h-3.1 already documented the sandbox-gitdir issue). Cap at ~5 parallel readonly to keep parent context under 200k when harvesting.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-37-S3-lock-design.codex.log:2284:/Users/martin/Downloads/LESSONS.md:185:- 2026-04-24 [testing][smoke] **Extract live-only scenarios into an offline-testable registry.** The original live-smoke was a 576-line monolith pinned to pamMachine — every new resource type meant forking the whole flow. Fix: create `scripts/smoke/scenarios.py` with `ScenarioSpec(name, resource_type, build_resources, verify)` objects, keep the identity/sandbox/destroy flow invariant, parametrise via `--scenario NAME`. The payoff is `tests/test_smoke_scenarios.py`: every scenario's `build_resources()` output goes through schema + typed-model + planner **without a tenant**, so schema drift (missing `url` on `pamRemoteBrowser`, wrong `database_type` enum) fails in milliseconds in CI instead of burning a tenant round-trip. Deferred scenarios (pamUser-standalone, adoption, drift, two-writer race) noted in V1_GA_CHECKLIST — the registry is the hosting pattern for them. Rule: when a live-only test runner accepts parametrisation, split the variant into a data object and test the variant offline through as much of the production pipeline as it touches.
