docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6224:   414	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-codex-fanout] **4 codex offline-bg + 1 Task subagent in parallel produced 4 cross-cited memos in ~5 min wall-clock and surfaced 1 immediately-landable schema drift fix (`bffa01b`).** Sprint 7h-36 fired: CDX-1 (multi-profile refactor), CDX-2 (concurrency audit), CDX-3 (capability census), CDX-4 (vault scenario design), Task agent (repo review summary). Wall-clock dominated by single-worker latency, so N parallel ≈ 1× sequential time. Total tokens used per worker logged in marker (CDX-2: 105k, CDX-3: 173k). Pattern: when investigation prompts are independent, well-scoped, cite-required (`file:line` mandatory in deliverable shape), and READONLY, parallel readonly fan-out is high-ROI vs serial codex_offline + serial parent reads. Anti-pattern: parallel WRITE-mode codex against same repo without git-worktree-per-worker (LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]` from 7h-3.1 already documented the sandbox-gitdir issue). Cap at ~5 parallel readonly to keep parent context under 200k when harvesting.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6237:   427	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][live-write-bg-via-nohup] **`codex_live.sh` is synchronous by design; background it with `nohup ... > log 2>&1 & disown` to run an offline-bg slice in parallel.** No wrapper needed. Poll via `ps -p <bash-pid>` for liveness and `ls -t /tmp/codex-live-*.log | head -1` for the latest live log. Sprint 7h-38 ran L1 live (~21min wall, in-run self-fixes + retries) alongside L3 offline-bg (~8min wall) for ~1.4x throughput vs serial. Pattern: launch L3 first via `codex_offline_bg.sh` (returns immediately with marker file), then launch L1 via `nohup codex_live.sh ... &`, then `AwaitShell` in 3-5min increments while polling both. Anti-pattern: trying to write a `codex_live_bg.sh` wrapper when `nohup` already does the job; one-shot orchestrator code stays out of `~/.cursor-daybook-sync/scripts/`.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6239:   429	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][live-worker-may-bypass-linked-worktree-ref] **A codex live-mode worker can land its commit on `origin/<branch>` without updating the linked-worktree's local branch ref or clearing its working-tree diff.** Symptoms after worker reports DONE: `git ls-remote origin <branch>` shows new SHA, but in the linked worktree `git log` shows the OLD base SHA and `git status` shows the same files as " M" (modified vs HEAD). Cause: live-mode codex appears to commit via plumbing or its own gitdir handling (different from offline-bg's auto-add-dir patch from LESSON `[orchestration][parent-commit]`). Recovery: skip the worktree entirely — parent merges `origin/<branch>` directly from the primary repo with `git merge --no-ff origin/<branch>`, then runs pytest in primary, pushes, and `git worktree remove --force` the dirty linked tree. The dirty diff there is just a stale copy of what's now on main, so `--force` removal is safe. Don't try to reconcile the linked worktree's HEAD — it's a distraction. Future fix in `codex_live.sh`: print local HEAD + remote HEAD after commit so the parent can spot the divergence in the launcher log immediately.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6241:   431	- 2026-04-27 [smoke][in-run-self-fix-during-live-proof] **A live-proof worker that hits real bugs during create→verify→destroy and self-fixes them inline with offline-test coverage is doing the right thing — but the LIVE-OK transcript should record the fixes as honest provenance, not hide them.** Sprint 7h-38 L1: vaultOneLogin live run hit 3 real bugs (provider sync-spinner contamination of in-proc `ls`/`get` JSON, vault empty-manifest stem coupling for delete-detection, sandbox cleanup using soft-delete instead of marker-guarded `rm --force`); worker self-fixed each + added offline tests, then re-ran the live cycle clean. The sanitized transcript's `notes` field captured the fixes. Rule: prompt allows ONE in-run minimal fix attempt; > 1 attempt → declare LIVE-FAIL, revert any partial fix, and let parent decide. Future template improvement: split "live-proof" (clean run, no fixes) from "live-debug" (run + fix + re-run + commit fix-with-transcript) into two slice templates so the LIVE-OK transcript stays clean of in-run bug notes when the goal is pure proof.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5d-operator-bootstrap.codex.log:6249:   439	- 2026-04-27 [daybook][regex-tightening] **Count pending daybook debt from the canonical Pending decisions section in WORKTREES.md with section-state parsing, not append-only JOURNAL/LESSONS substring scans that preserve historical references forever.** Section-parser enters on `^##\s+Pending decisions\b`, exits on next `^##\s+`, counts unchecked checkbox + numbered rows that are NOT closed (`~~`, `**DONE`, `[x]`, `_[CLOSED`). 5-case offline test at `~/.cursor-daybook-sync/scripts/test_pending_count.py`. Closes 7h-35 LESSON `[daybook][regex-by-reference-inflation]`. Migration risk audited at `agent_review_loop.py` callers + boot/stop hooks; review-latest is fail-open so a broken patch couldn't block session close anyway.
