docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5e-bus-decision.codex.log:946:351:- 2026-04-26 [codex-sandbox][shared-object-store] **Linked worktrees need TWO directories writable beyond the cwd, not one: the per-worktree gitdir (`<primary>/.git/worktrees/<n>/`) AND the common gitdir (`<primary>/.git/`).** First fix patched `codex_offline.sh` to add only the per-worktree gitdir from `git rev-parse --git-dir`; workers immediately hit a second `Operation not permitted` writing blobs to `<primary>/.git/objects/`. The common gitdir holds the shared object store + refs that every linked worktree commits into. Final fix: also auto-add `git rev-parse --git-common-dir` (with dedup when equal to per-worktree gitdir for normal clones). Pattern: when sandbox-tightening blocks ANY git operation in a linked worktree, the answer is always BOTH gitdirs (`--git-dir` + `--git-common-dir`); a partial fix that only adds one is a recurring failure mode that re-bites at the next operation. Verified by 3 cov slices (redact, schema, normalize) all landing successfully via parent-commit in the same session — workers only need to be re-launched if the deliverable itself is wrong, not if the tooling layer is busted.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5e-bus-decision.codex.log:948:368:- 2026-04-26 [codex-cli][bg-detach] **Background launchers must use `nohup` + runner-script + redirect-from-/dev/null, not `( ... ) &`.** Cursor's Shell tool starts a fresh bash per command that exits when the command returns. Naive `( ... ) &` subshells inherit that bash as their parent and catch SIGHUP when it exits — the cleanup block (writing `STATE=DONE` to the marker) never runs. First version of `codex_offline_bg.sh` had this bug; bus.py worker completed a clean READONLY-OK memo in the log but the marker stayed `LAUNCHED` forever. Fix: write the codex command + cleanup into a runner script (`/tmp/codex-offline-<ts>-<pid>.runner.sh`) and launch via `nohup bash $RUNNER </dev/null >/dev/null 2>&1 &`. `disown` alone is not enough on macOS bash inside an exiting parent. Verified: trivial test prompt now writes `STATE=DONE EXIT_CODE=0` correctly within seconds of codex finishing.
