docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5e-bus-decision.codex.log:1132:   379	- 2026-04-26 [live-test][skip-by-default] **Live-tenant tests collected only when `KEEPER_LIVE_TENANT=1` AND each test's declared `requires=(...)` env vars are present; gate enforced at pytest-collection time, not runtime.** `tests/live/conftest.py` walks every collected item, looks for `pytest.mark.live(requires=(...))`, and adds a skip marker if `KEEPER_LIVE_TENANT` isn't `1` or any required env var is missing. Why collection-time vs runtime: a runtime check (`if not os.environ.get(...): pytest.skip(...)`) still imports the test module, runs fixtures, and shows the test in the report as "skipped" with a Python-level reason — workable but noisier and import-time crashes leak. Collection-time skip means `pytest tests/` reports exactly one skipped item per live test, no fixture work, no module-level imports of live-only deps. Pattern: any test category that depends on out-of-band setup (creds, GPU, network) should gate at collection so the default offline run is metrics-clean.
docs/sprint-memos/7h-40-V5e-bus-decision.codex.log:1138:   385	- 2026-04-26 [orchestration][parallel-readonly-memos] **4 parallel offline-readonly Codex workers complete in wall-time bounded by the largest single worker, not summed; on a clean main with shared workspace, no per-worker worktree is needed.** Sprint 7h-14: 4 schema-design memos (P10/P11/P12/P13 of V2 lineup) dispatched simultaneously via `codex_safe_launch.sh --repo "$SDK"` against a single clean `main` checkout. P11 (largest scope, enterprise) finished at 4min; P12/P13/P10 finished within 1min of P11. Total wall: ~5min vs ~30+ min serial. Shared workspace works because read-only workers can't collide on writes; the parent just extracts each worker's stdout from `/tmp/codex-offline-*-<pid>.log`. Pattern: (a) read-only workers parallelize trivially, share workspace; (b) write workers need worktrees + serial execution per branch; (c) wall-time predictor for parallel readonly = max(per-worker estimate), not sum. Practical implication: when the parent is between product slices and has 3+ research questions queued, ALWAYS dispatch them in parallel rather than asking sequentially.
